
TY  - JOUR
T1  - “Implicit” and “Explicit” CSR: A Conceptual Framework for a Comparative Understanding of Corporate Social Responsibility
AU  - Matten, Dirk
AU  - Moon, Jeremy
Y1  - 2008/04/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.31193458
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.31193458
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 404
EP  - 424
VL  - 33
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We address the question of how and why corporate social responsibility (CSR) differs among countries and how and why it changes. Applying two schools of thought in institutional theory, we conceptualize, first, the differences between CSR in the United States and Europe and, second, the recent rise of CSR in Europe. We also delineate the potential of our framework for application to other parts of the global economy.
AB  - We address the question of how and why corporate social responsibility (CSR) differs among countries and how and why it changes. Applying two schools of thought in institutional theory, we conceptualize, first, the differences between CSR in the United States and Europe and, second, the recent rise of CSR in Europe. We also delineate the potential of our framework for application to other parts of the global economy.
