TY  - JOUR
T1  - Industry Determinants of the “Merger Versus Alliance” Decision
AU  - Yin, Xiaoli
AU  - Shanley, Mark
Y1  - 2008/04/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.31193515
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.31193515
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 473
EP  - 491
VL  - 33
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Mergers and acquisitions (M&As) and alliances are potential alternative choices for managers. We propose that three dimensions of industry conditions are likely to be influential in such choices: (1) industry demands on firms to make significant commitment, (2) the environmental pressures for flexibility, and (3) the limitations on firm choices stemming from industry concentration and institutional conditions. We develop propositions about how differences across these three dimensions influence the choices that firms make between M&As and alliances.
AB  - Mergers and acquisitions (M&As) and alliances are potential alternative choices for managers. We propose that three dimensions of industry conditions are likely to be influential in such choices: (1) industry demands on firms to make significant commitment, (2) the environmental pressures for flexibility, and (3) the limitations on firm choices stemming from industry concentration and institutional conditions. We develop propositions about how differences across these three dimensions influence the choices that firms make between M&As and alliances.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.31193515
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2008.31193515
Y2  - 2026/04/24
