TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Impact of Multinational Enterprise Strategy on Indigenous Enterprises: Horizontal Spillovers and Crowding Out in Developing Countries
AU  - Spencer, Jennifer W.
Y1  - 2008/04/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.31193230
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.31193230
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 341
EP  - 361
VL  - 33
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Under what conditions does a multinational enterprise's (MNE's) investment in a developing country produce spillovers for local firms operating in the same industry? In this paper I view firms as unique configurations of tacit and codified knowledge, and I propose that the strategies pursued by an MNE will determine whether the investment will create positive externalities, through knowledge diffusion and provision of public goods, or negative externalities, through a crowding out effect on indigenous enterprises.
AB  - Under what conditions does a multinational enterprise's (MNE's) investment in a developing country produce spillovers for local firms operating in the same industry? In this paper I view firms as unique configurations of tacit and codified knowledge, and I propose that the strategies pursued by an MNE will determine whether the investment will create positive externalities, through knowledge diffusion and provision of public goods, or negative externalities, through a crowding out effect on indigenous enterprises.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.31193230
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2008.31193230
Y2  - 2026/04/24
