TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Role of Affect in the Entrepreneurial Process
AU  - Baron, Robert A.
Y1  - 2008/04/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.31193166
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.31193166
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 328
EP  - 340
VL  - 33
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Research findings indicate that the feelings and moods individuals experience (i.e., their affect) influence many aspects of cognition and behavior. Extending these findings to entrepreneurship, I suggest that affect influences several aspects of entrepreneurs' cognition and, hence, important elements of the entrepreneurial process. I propose a theoretical framework for understanding the role of affect in key aspects of entrepreneurship (e.g., opportunity recognition, resource acquisition).
AB  - Research findings indicate that the feelings and moods individuals experience (i.e., their affect) influence many aspects of cognition and behavior. Extending these findings to entrepreneurship, I suggest that affect influences several aspects of entrepreneurs' cognition and, hence, important elements of the entrepreneurial process. I propose a theoretical framework for understanding the role of affect in key aspects of entrepreneurship (e.g., opportunity recognition, resource acquisition).
